      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;co-source&#34; class=&#34;headerLink&#34;&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &lt;a href=&#34;#co-source&#34; class=&#34;header-mark&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Co source&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;h2 id=&#34;intro&#34; class=&#34;headerLink&#34;&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &lt;a href=&#34;#intro&#34; class=&#34;header-mark&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Intro&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;h3 id=&#34;protected-inner-source-recap&#34; class=&#34;headerLink&#34;&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &lt;a href=&#34;#protected-inner-source-recap&#34; class=&#34;header-mark&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Protected Inner Source Recap&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Protected Inner Source is a source code sharing strategy that defines an intermediate model between Open Source and Inner Source. The analogy used here is that &lt;a href=&#34;https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/programming-guide/classes-and-structs/access-modifiers#summary-table&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener noreferrer&#34;&gt;C# Access Modifiers&lt;/a&gt; define a &amp;lsquo;Protected Internal Class&amp;rsquo; as an intermediate between &amp;lsquo;Public Class&amp;rsquo; and &amp;lsquo;Internal Class&amp;rsquo;. The purpose of which is to be more closed off between assemblies than &amp;lsquo;Public Class&amp;rsquo;, yet more open for reuse than &amp;lsquo;Internal Class&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
